\f2\i \cf0 How Can I Control What Happens To Files Downloaded Via The Rumpus Web File Manager?\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\li720\ql\qnatural

\f0\i0 \cf0 \
Rumpus sends files to the browser, but it is up to the browser to decide what to do with the file. If it's an HTML file, for example, the browser will display it, by default.\
\
With that said, you do have options...\
\
First, most browsers will give you other options for what to do with files that are retrieved from a server. In typical Mac browsers, for example, if you hold down the Control key and click and hold on a link, a pop-up menu will appear that gives you several choices, including "Download Link To Disk" or some similar option. Again, remember, Rumpus can only deliver the data... Some work may need to be done at the browser in order to process the data the way you need.\
\
Even from the server side, however, you have some control. The way browsers determine how to process the data they are receiving is by the file's "Content-Type". This is a bit of information that is sent by the server as part of the file download. In Rumpus, you can control the Content Type using the File Types window to edit each filename extension (the portion of the filename after the "dot", which typically specifies what type of data is contained in the file). If you wish, you can change the Content-Type for various filename extensions so that the browser handles those files accordingly.\
\
Determining the correct Content-Type for a given file type is the trickiest and most server-specific component of the process of serving files for download. Rumpus comes preconfigured with dozens of common File Types which tell browsers how to handle many common files. You may, however, need to add entries to the preconfigured list, or change specific entries. For example, Rumpus comes preset to serve files with the suffix ".html" with a Content-Type of "text/html", which virtually all browsers will interpret to mean that the file should be displayed in the browser window. If, however, you would like HTML files saved to disk by default, you will need to change the Content-Type to represent binary data, which browsers will typically save to disk. (The most generic binary Content-Type is "application/octet-stream", for example.)\
\
When working with files, try changing the filename suffix to better represent the data in the file, or to simply experiment with how various browsers process the data after it is downloaded. Finally, for examples of various filename extensions and their associated Content-Types, look in the preference settings of your favorite Web browser. Most browsers come preconfigured with many, many Content-Types and helper applications.\
